<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-807-556  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 807 556.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DBMS  Sept 1990 v3 n10 p36(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Distributed databases. (guidelines to implementing a distributeddatabase)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Edelstein, Herb.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Distributed databases contain data that, although distributed overdifferent networked computers, appear to both users and programsto be from a single database.andP;  Twelve rules that a distributeddatabase should follow are discussed.andP;  In contrast to centralizeddatabases, distributed databases allow data to be managed locally,reducing communications and enhancing local autonomy.andP;  Businesspressures are forcing decentralizing companies to turn todistributed databases.andP;  Rapid growth in computing power makesdistributed databases feasible.andP;  A distributed database should beindependent of hardware, operating systems and network software.andO;Although many components of distributed databases are available,each implementation fails to deal with key aspects of distributeddatabase management.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Distributed Data BasesData Base DesignData Base Management SystemsGuidelines.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   The 12 rules of distributed databases according to Chris Date.andO;(table)Distributed data. (chart)Optimizer functions. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>